Writing an R function

If you have not written an R function before you might want to check out the Functions chapter in R for Data Science (Wickham, Çetinkaya-Rundel, and Grolemund 2023)


getBS &lt;- function() {
  # expand out
  exp &lt;- eg.wang2000 |&gt;
    mutate(
      r1 = (rate / 100) * size,
      r0 = (1 - (rate / 100)) * size
    ) |&gt;
    select(pop, ethnicity, age_group, r0:r1) |&gt;
    pivot_longer(r0:r1, names_to = "r", values_to = "n") |&gt;
    mutate(n = as.integer(n)) |&gt;
    uncount(n)

  # sample for each pop
  # lapply fits the function to each level of the data
  bs &lt;- lapply(unique(eg.wang2000$pop), \(p) {
    slice_sample(exp[exp$pop == p, ], prop = 1, replace = TRUE) |&gt;
      group_by(ethnicity, age_group) |&gt;
      reframe(
        pop = p,
        size = n(),
        rate = mean(r == "r1") * 100
      ) |&gt;
      ungroup()
  })

  do.call(rbind, bs)
}

Bootstrapping in practice

Now we can calculate standard errors for these estimates


bsamps |&gt;
  select(k, dgo) |&gt;
  unnest(dgo) |&gt;
  group_by(k, factor) |&gt;
  reframe(diff = rate[pop == "female"] - rate[pop == "male"]) |&gt;
  group_by(factor) |&gt;
  reframe(se = sd(diff))

# A tibble: 4 × 2
  factor              se
  &lt;chr&gt;            &lt;dbl&gt;
1 age_group_struct 0.296
2 crude            1.32 
3 ethnicity_struct 0.328
4 rate             1.27

